        <article id="scrollmonitor" class="mb-4 mb-md-6">
          <h3>
            </h3>
<p>scrollMonitor</p>
          
          <div>
            <p><a href="https://github.com/stutrek/scrollMonitor">GitHub</a>, <a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/scrollmonitor">npm</a>
            </p>
            <p>The scroll monitor allows us to receive events when elements enter or exit the viewport. It does this using watcher objects, which watch an element and trigger events.</p>
            <p>Leap uses scrollMonitor to manage 'sticky' elements that stick to the top of the window or beneath the nav.</p>
            <p>You can make an element such as a <code>.navbar</code> or <code>.navbar-dark</code> stick to the viewport top by adding the <code>data-sticky="top"</code> attribute or if you want an in-page nav to scroll with the page, then stick below
              the main nav, use <code>data-sticky="below-nav"</code>. If the sticky element has a <code>section</code> ancestor it will switch to stick to the bottom of that section when scrolled into view.</p>

          </div>
        </article>

        <article id="smooth-scroll" class="mb-4 mb-md-6">
